# Terraform Pattern

## Repo separation

The walkthrough docs (`aws-eks-walkthrough`) never contain Terraform code. All infrastructure lives in dedicated external repos:

| Repo | Purpose |
| ---- | ------- |
| `aws-eks-terraform` | Terraform modules and walkthrough entry point |
| `aws-eks-platform` | ArgoCD/GitOps manifests (platform batch, future) |

## Expected Terraform repo layout

When documenting or referencing `aws-eks-terraform`, assume this structure:

```plaintext
aws-eks-terraform/
├── modules/
│   ├── vpc/
│   │   ├── main.tf
│   │   ├── variables.tf
│   │   └── outputs.tf
│   ├── eks/
│   │   ├── main.tf
│   │   ├── variables.tf
│   │   └── outputs.tf
│   └── platform/        # future
│       ├── main.tf
│       ├── variables.tf
│       └── outputs.tf
└── walkthrough/
    ├── main.tf           # calls modules in order
    ├── variables.tf
    ├── outputs.tf
    └── terraform.tfvars.example   # always present; never commit .tfvars
```

## Module conventions

- Each module has exactly: `main.tf`, `variables.tf`, `outputs.tf`.
- No `terraform.tfstate` or `.tfvars` files inside `modules/`.
- Variables use `description` and `type` on every declaration.
- Outputs expose the IDs and ARNs consumed by the next module.
- Tags are always passed via a `var.tags` map and merged with a `Name` tag.

## Naming conventions

- Resources: `<module>_<resource_type>` (e.g. `aws_vpc.main`, `aws_subnet.private`).
- Variables and outputs: snake_case, descriptive (e.g. `private_subnet_ids`, `cluster_endpoint`).
- Workspace entry point lives in `walkthrough/`, not at the repo root.

## terraform.tfvars.example

Every `walkthrough/` folder must contain a `terraform.tfvars.example` file with all required variables and placeholder values. Readers copy it to `terraform.tfvars` before running `terraform apply`.

## Documenting Terraform steps in the walkthrough

1. Show the relevant HCL in a code block with `title="modules/<section>/main.tf"`.
2. Use line highlighting `{line}` to draw attention to key settings.
3. Show `terraform init` then `terraform apply` in terminal code blocks.
4. Show verification with both a Terraform output tab and an AWS CLI tab inside `<Tabs syncKey="tool">`.

## ArgoCD / GitOps repo (future — platform batch)

When the platform batch is written, reference `aws-eks-platform` which follows a layout like:

```plaintext
aws-eks-platform/
├── bootstrap/
│   ├── bootstrap.sh
│   ├── argocd-install.yaml
│   ├── argocd-values.yaml
│   └── root-eks.yaml
├── clusters/
│   └── eks/
│       ├── infrastructure.yaml
│       └── platform-apps.yaml
└── infrastructure/
    ├── aws-load-balancer-controller/
    ├── aws-ebs-csi-driver/
    ├── external-dns/
    └── cert-manager/
```

Update this rule when the platform repo is created.

